review_blob: Bubbles nicely with a light head. Light aroma. Hoppy front, ends slightly dry but sweet. Mild-bodied. Initial tasting reminded me of a dessert wine.
beer_name: Flying Dog Old Scratch Amber Lager

review_blob: Citrus-lavendar nose which reminded me of light Full Sail Pale Ale. Perhaps I am giving it too much credit there. Slightly carbonated with no head. A sweet palate that could be discerned as gumball-like. Lacked the nice bitter trail that I look for in a true pale ale. An Ale/Lager? that tastes of a weak pale and a decent lager. This new arrival is standard fare. Tried after a Hollande 1620, another new arrival.
Carbonated with tiny, tiny bubbles. Expecting skunk. Got back light, fruity aroma. Buttery front with an so slightly bitter hop trail.
Fresh batch. Lightly carbonated. Easy to drink with little taste, but a noticeable body. Finish reminiscent of apple cider.

Not a bad choice for $3.00. Looks like root beer. Slightly metallic nose. Not watery-thin, but light bodied with a faint stout character. A lager with a discernable dark beer flavor. One of my favorite bottles.

2000. Off tap. Piney hops nose. Dark orange, dull amber appearance. Head lasts forever. Light undertones of  alcohol throughout. Perhaps it was the aged keg. Explosive hops kick right from the start. Bittering through the front to the dry, crisp finish. Malty sweetness builds from the start and culminates at the end. Interesting way to balance this particularly hoppy brew. I still prefer the Stone IPA 5th, but this one holds its own otherwise.

Deep brown in color. Light and faint roasted nose. Short front exhibited light and faint malted coffee flavors. Transition was abrupt and unnatural. Finish was unimpressive, definitely below-standard lager fare. Certainly not a Guinness/Bass.
Smoother than most domestics. Easy drinking, but lacks characteristic flavors. MHL typifies American domestic beer.

A Korean Budweiser with a sweeter palate and a crisper, drier finish. Golden yellow color. Carbonation dissipates quickly when left to warm. Hints of apple accompanying the signature Budweiser hop trail. A light-bodied and thin taste that does Korean food no justice. Inferior to Budweiser.

Cinnamon-red appearance. A light Newcastle Brown in an amber body. Little taste and character. Others chimed in with bad taste and no character. Will try this one again to be sure. This one certainly fails to hold its own against their wonderful IPA.
Golden in color. Light honey, strong lavander nose. Lavander and pine palate. Flavor reminds me of flowers of PNW forests? A fair, light rendition of a lavendar pale.
Strong honey, floral scents. Crisp, dry front. Not as big of a hops explosion I had expected, but a clear hops mid. Crisp, dry finish with a distinctive flavor. Not bad on the third tasting.

Strong, skunky aroma with a slightly sweet finish in the nose. Medium-bodied. Surprisingly smooth with clover honey notes. Lightly carbonated finish that is both balanced and ever so slightly sweet.
Superior to Heineken. Have I rated this brew too high? Will try again.
Metallic nose from the bottle and glass. Slight malted chocolate aroma. Clean lager front. Change of malted flavors midway. Finish ended slightly sweet throughout. Easy to drink, light session brew.

Light, gainy nose. Smooth, albeit with an ever so slight metallic undertone. Malty sweet background throughout, particularly in the finish. Ends with a hoppy trail reminiscent of Budweiser, which I favor. The neutrality of Newcastle Brown. Solid Mexican beer that is usually found fresh in the LA, CA region.

The worst beverage I have tried to date. Nose  was alcoholic, although it did not demonstrate an 8.1%. Front was sharp, which lead to a metallic, sour mid. Ended with a poorly malted alcoholic finish. Not to the point of rubbing alcohol, but certainly headed in that direction. Now I know what a $1.56 beer tastes like. We ended up pouring the entire can minus a cupful down the drain.

Off tap at a reputed bar in Pasadena, CA. A glorified Budweiser without the tailing hoppiness. Easy-drinking transitional beer that lacks much character. I was expecting more from this oldie-but-newbie import. But then again, this is a pils. Mild-mannered palate that changes very little from start to finish. Even tempered through and through. Good for a glass and then off the the ales...

Canned and on tap. Deep, dark color with a mid-bodied texture. Good session beer as it carries with it flavor characteristics not found in other lower abv beers. Creamy. Tastes of milk chocolate with a welcome bitter roasted trail. Good with chocolate chip cookies of all sorts.

Nitro can. Smooth and slightly sweet with a creamy head. Guinness-like when cold. It has a watery-light, sweet flavor that I find inferior to the watery-light roasted flavors of Guinness Draught, which I like to compare it with.

Dark, dark brown. Almost syrupy in body. Frothy head not creamy, but carbonated. Dissipates quickly. Nose is of dark, roasted coffee with an alcoholic finish. Undertones of alcohol throughout the mid. Overtones of alcohol through the finish. Where did the roasted coffee go? Light, lingering  bittering. Earlier Rating: 12/11/2001 Total Score: 3.2Watery, but thick, if that makes any sense. Draught is much better. About the same color, smoother, and more chocolatey. Go for the draught.

A deceivingly dark beer with a deceiving lack of  character. Nice, open aroma of malt. Front is very short. Mid is  slightly sweet with a light hint of malted grains. Ends clean, leaving something to be desired.
Carbonation dominates the scene if left out to warm. Inferior to Heineken Dark.
Deep, fruity sweet aroma. Fuller bodied than most lagers. I favor this one warm or slightly cool, which allows the flavors to develop. Nice barley finish.

Fresh, natural fruity hops nose. This brew does an excellent job of hiding its relatively high alcohol content. Front develops as the glass warms. Clean, fresh hops-heavy mid. Nice bitter finish. Good example of a West Coast IPA

The very first beer that I enjoyed solely for its flavor. A bit more carbonated than I would prefer, but semi-bold, extra clean hoppiness more than makes up for it. Nice, very tolerable bittering at the end. Enjoyable and one of my favorite readily-available beers.
Light fruity nose. Light front and mid. Light grainy end. Can be found fresh in the L.A. area, so quality was not bad at all.
Aroma was very hoppy. Front was short, but flavorful. Mid and finish were uninspiring. Ended clean, but with little punch or pizazz. as was the clesn finish.
Tastes like Chinese plum juice with carbonation. Sour and sweet, in that order. Beer that tastes like plum juice.
Champagne beer. Sweet aroma reminiscent of caramel candy. Sugary in the mid and at the end. Did not notice the purported hoppy finish. Was not as dry as expected. Good only as a dessert brew.

Lightly carbonated. Nose is partucularly hoppy. Flavor is balance of lavendar and hops with malty sweet, faintly bitter finish. Very good extra pale ale. More flavor and character than similar offerings from Full Sail and SLO.

This is something you have with a friend and taste with three. I liken it to the style of their 5th Anniversary IPA: Solid character; Hard, but clean bitterness. Palate changed four or five times from the end of the front through to the finish. Usually found fresh in LA. Alcoholic finish lingers,  supplemented by a sweet, tapering background. Cool, but not warm is best for this puppy.
Frothy head with a slightly alcoholic nose. Mid tastes of fruitcake with a slightly sweet finish. Nice...

Aroma was sour and a bit skunky. Carbonated head that fizzled away quick. Malt heavy towards the end and finish. Inferior to Budweiser. Skunky taste throughout. I want to give this beer a higher rating. Will have to try this beer when fresh. This is really an unfair asessment of this brew.

2001. Citrusy, alcoholic nose. Short, bitter front. Fuller body than SNPA with a high hops mid and a mellow malty sweet background. More assertive malt background would have provided a better balanced beer. Lingering, dry hops finish. Its almost as if the higher alcohol content adds spiciness to the brew.
Easy drinking, but sour nonetheless. Between a Corona and a Heineken. Light grainy finish that saves this beer from Beer Hell.

Had it on tap at TGI Fridays. A glorified Newcastle Brown. Rough and dirty in the front, but decent malty sweet background at the end. Somewhat overrated. I prefer their Pale.


ty in the front, good flavor

large, firm head when poured properly. Excellent example of a clear and tasty hefe. Slightly nutty with strong banana overtones in the nose and the palate. Although this brew certainly does not need it, a slice of lemon does bring out the floral and citrus scents. Good either way.

Transitional beer. Starts smooth and uncharacteristic, ends smooth and uncharacteristic. Easy drinking mild that goes down better in the bottle. Taste is similar, but more pronounced on tap. That said, I really have to try it in the can.

A tinge of alcohol in the nose. Smooth start with a dirty, uncomplex front. Off tap, front is clean, nearly tasteless. Character not apparent until the relatively clean finish. Drinkable, but lacks the flavorful notes of an Edelweiss. Decent summer brew, but this is one of those beers that should really be had on tap. This rating is assuming a bottle tasting. A good 3.3 off tap.

Thick and dark. Roasted complexity led up to a burnt bitterness at the end. The dry bitterness was unwelcome in that regard, but the mid is certainly something to try to comprehend. Noticed three or four changes in palate with every mouthful.
Definitely dark, but thinner than a stout. Lacked the roasted complexity that I was looking for. Finished a bit sharp.

Popular and usually found fresh in the Los Angeles region. Best cold where the carbonation does not affect the palate as much. Nice grainy, hoppy finish develops in the midddle of the finish and lingers. Reminds me a bit of SNPA. The King of Beers? No, but certainly not the court jester either.
Not as smooth as High Life, but carries more character. Definitely drinkable. Smoother than Budweiser, but less flavor in the finish.

Pale in color. Alcoholic, but acceptable nose. A tad bit sour in the front. Carbonated mid with mild yeast undertones and clover honey overtones. Fresh grain finish with honey undertones. Must try again.

Searched for and tried this beer after seeing it listed as one of Ratebeer.coms Top Beers. Coffee-like aroma that wafts from the bottle and from the glass. Heavily roasted coffee aroma with chocolate under and overtones. The most alcoholic brew I have ever had and one where the taste of alcohol was very well masked. Very complex palate that seemed to change flavors with every mouthful. A bit bold for me right now, but I see where this brew is coming from. Served up after dinner as a dessert sounds good to me. Ill try it again in a few weeks.

Fresh and off tap at a busy, well-versed bar. Mid to full-bodied with a foreground dominated by hops and a background of malty sweetness that kicks in at the end of the front. Robust mid of grains and more grains that tapers off to a lingering sweetness. An unbalanced, but balanced finish that should be savored.
One of the best offerings from Anchor Brewing and my favorite from them. A hops-head I am and this is an excellent variation on the theme. Not as hopped up, but imparts great flavor.
A watered-down Corona. That said, somewhat enjoyable. This is what Coors Light should have been: Not too sweet, not too sour. Middle ground brew that I usually find fresh.
Light and clean with an artificial dryness. Mild but pronounced lager. Goes well with food as it cleans the palate with a dry, lightly-hopped aftertaste.

beer_brewer_name: Yakima Brewing And Malting Co./Bert Grants Real Ales
review_blob: Fruity nose with just a hint of alcohol. Sweet and a bit spicy. Interesting grains. Chocolate was roasted, not quite as creamy as or flavorful as Guiness Draught. Slightly bitter, lingering finish. Pronounced hop-kick aided by a sweet mid. Good winter brew.
beer_name: Bert Grants Deep Powder Winter Ale

review_blob: Huge fruit-intense aroma that effectively masks the relatively high alcohol content of this hops-head brew. Short, bitter front. Sweet mid with a very pronounced hop-kick-and-a-jump. Crisp, bitter, lasting  finish. Lingering hop palate.
